prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Group 1
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: First group of sources, located mainly to the south west.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
We propose to observe 87 M4.75-G0 stars (M* ~ 0.2-2 Msun) in Upper Sco that are surrounded by disks. These stars will be observed in the 880 micron continuum and 12CO J=3-2. For the nominal weather conditions at this frequency, the program will require 8.1 hours including calibrations and overhead.
Receiver Band ------------- The submillimeter flux scales with frequency as approximately nu^2.5 if the emission is optically thin. Considering both receive noise and atmospheric conditions, Band 7 (850 micron) is the most sensitive of the ALMA bands to dust mass for a fixed integration time.
Free-free emission can contaminate the dust continuum if the source is within ~ 0.3 pc of a O6-type star. None of the stars in Upper Sco have such an early spectral type. The low mass stars that we are observing are spread out over ~ 25 pc projected on the sky, so we can safely assume that the 850 micron flux originates from thermal dust emission.
Array Configuration ------------------- We request a resolution of 0.4 arcsec, which most closely corresponds to configuration C34-3. This angular resolution is sufficient to resolve the dust disks and provide the maximum information on the disk properties. The maximum angular scale that is sampled in the C34-3 configuation is 5.2 arcsec, which is substantially larger than the expected disk size. Given that the Upper Sco OB Association is no longer embedded in a molecular cloud, there is no contamination from a dense molecular cloud to the gas and dust emission. For scheduling purposes, 0.3-0.5 arcsec resolution observations are suitable for this program (i.e., configurations C34-2, C34-3, and C34-4).
Correlator setup ---------------- Since the main goal of the survey is to detect the dust continuum, we will configure the bands to 1.875 GHz bandwidth to maximize the continuum sensitivity. The primary band is placed on the 12CO line with 0.8 km/s resolution, which is sufficient to resolve the spectral lines, which will extend over a few km/s. The remaining three bands were placed in portions of the bands with the highest atmospheric transmission to optimize continuum sensitivity. One of these bands is also observed with 0.8 km/s resolution for serendipitous line detections while maintaining reasonable data rates. The remaining bands are placed in continuum mode only.
Sensitivity ----------- We aim to achieve 10x times better sensitivity than the only existing submillimeter continuum survey of disks in Upper Sco, which achieved noise level of 0.8 mJy at 1200 micron (Mathews et al. 2012). We thus require a RMS noise level of 0.15 mJy at 880 micron assuming the continuum emission varies with frequency as nu^2.5. This will enable us to detect dust masses as low as 1 Mearth at 3sigma. This can be achieved in 2.16 minutes of on-source integration time for the above correlator setup according to the ALMA Observing Tool.
The spectral line sensitivity at this angular resolution is 1.5 K according to the ALMA sensitivity calculator. Given the 12CO emission is optically thick and the typical disk temperature is ~ 25 K (Andrews et al. 2013), this sensitivity should easily detect 12CO if present.
Imaging requirements -------------------- Given the sources are compact (< 1 arcsec in diameter), there are no stringent imaging requirements and the 2 minute snapshot integrations are sufficient to image the sources.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The lifetime of primordial, optically thick disks around young stars places empirical constraints on the timescale to form planetary systems. Submillimeter observations play a critical role in quantifying the evolution since the emission is optically thin over most of the disk and probes the cool material where most of the disk mass resides and where most planets form. We request time with ALMA to image the dust and gas toward a complete sample of disks around stars in the 5-11 Myr old Upper Scorpius OB Association that have spectral types between M4.75 and G0, corresponding to stellar masses between about 0.2 and 2 Msun. Upper Sco is the nearest OB association of this age, and thereby provides an opportunity to obtain sensitive measurements of the disk properties at the end stage in the lifetime of primordial disks. By comparing the dust emission from disks in Upper Sco with existing continuum observations of 1 Myr stars in Taurus, we aim to measure 1) the amount of dust that is dispersed from disks on 5-10 Myr timescales, 2) the efficiency of disk dispersal as a function of stellar mass, and 3) how the dust mass evolves between evolutionary states.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Circumstellar disks, exoplanets and the solar system
